markArea.data.desc:
 The scope of the area is defined by data, which is an array with two item, representing the left-top point and the right-bottom point of rectangle area. Each item can be defined as follows: 

1. Specify the coordinate in screen coordinate system using [x][0], [y][1], where the unit is pixel (e.g., the value is 5), or percent (e.g., the value is '35%').

1. Specify the coordinate in data coordinate system (i.e., cartesian) using [coord][2], which can be also set as 'min', 'max', 'average' (e.g, coord: [23, 'min'], or coord: ['average', 'max']).
1. Locate the point on the min value or max value of series.data using [type][3], where [valueIndex][4] or [valueDim][5] can be used to specify the dimension on which the min, max or average are calculated.
1. If in cartesian, you can only specify xAxis or yAxis to define a mark area based on only X or Y axis, see sample [scatter-weight][6]

The priority follows as above if more than one above definition used. 

    data: [


        [
            {
                name: 'From average to max',
                type: 'average'
            },
            {
                type: 'max'
            }
        ],

        [
            {
                name: 'Mark area between two points in data coordiantes',
                coord: [10, 20]
            },
            {
                coord: [20, 30]
            }
        ], [
            {
                name: 'From 60 to 80',
                yAxis: 60
            },
            {
                yAxis: 80
            }
        ], [
            {
                name: 'Mark area covers all data'
                coord: ['min', 'min']
            },
            {
                coord: ['max', 'max']
            }
        ],
    [
            {
                name: 'Mark area in two screen points',
                x: 100,
                y: 100
            }, {
                x: '90%',
                y: '10%'
            }
        ]
    ]


